type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>It follows from our <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-002T.xml"
addr="jms-002T"
title="Characterization of positivity in terms of partial elements">characterization</fr:link> of <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-001M.xml"
addr="jms-001M"
title="The positive elements of a pointed dcpo">positivity</fr:link> in terms of partial elements that an element <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a: A]]></fr:tex> of a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-001S.xml"
addr="jms-001S"
title="Pointed dcpo">pointed</fr:link> dcpo <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-001M.xml"
addr="jms-001M"
title="The positive elements of a pointed dcpo">positive</fr:link> if and only if it is <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-002W.xml"
addr="jms-002W"
title="The strictly-below relation">strictly above</fr:link> the bottom element, i.e. <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot \sqsubset  a]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>(See also Proposition 6.2.12 of <fr:link
type="local"
href="dejong-2023-thesis.xml"
addr="dejong-2023-thesis"
title="Domain theory in constructive and predicative univalent foundations">Tom de Jong’s thesis</fr:link>.)</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:backmatter></fr:tree>